# this repository is for understanding Basics linux commands for Devops


# Linux basics commands

# Linux Commands Cheat Sheet

## File and Directory Commands

- **ls**: List directory contents
  ```bash
  ls [options] [directory]
  ```

- **pwd**: Print current working directory
  ```bash
  pwd
  ```

- **cd**: Change directory
  ```bash
  cd [directory]
  ```

- **mkdir**: Create a new directory
  ```bash
  mkdir [options] directory_name
  ```

- **rmdir**: Remove an empty directory
  ```bash
  rmdir directory_name
  ```

- **rm**: Remove files or directories
  ```bash
  rm [options] file_or_directory
  ```

- **cp**: Copy files and directories
  ```bash
  cp [options] source destination
  ```

- **mv**: Move or rename files
  ```bash
  mv [options] source destination
  ```

- **touch**: Create an empty file or update the timestamp
  ```bash
  touch file_name
  ```

## File Viewing and Editing

- **cat**: Display the contents of a file
  ```bash
  cat file_name
  ```

- **less**: View file content one page at a time
  ```bash
  less file_name
  ```

- **more**: Display file content (scrollable output)
  ```bash
  more file_name
  ```

- **echo**: Display a message or output text to a file
  ```bash
  echo "message" > file_name
  ```

## Process Management

- **ps**: Display currently running processes
  ```bash
  ps [options]
  ```

- **top**: Display real-time system processes
  ```bash
  top
  ```

- **vmstat**: Report virtual memory statistics
  ```bash
  vmstat [options]
  ```

- **kill**: Terminate processes
  ```bash
  kill [PID]
  ```

## Networking Commands

- **ping**: Test network connectivity
  ```bash
  ping hostname_or_IP
  ```

- **dig**: Query DNS servers
  ```bash
  dig domain_name
  ```

- **ss**: Display active connections
  ```bash
  ss [options]
  ```

- **telnet**: Open a telnet session
  ```bash
  telnet hostname
  ```

## User Management

- **who**: Display logged-in users
  ```bash
  who
  ```

- **whoami**: Display the current user
  ```bash
  whoami
  ```

- **id**: Display user ID (UID) and group ID (GID)
  ```bash
  id [username]
  ```

- **su**: Switch user
  ```bash
  su [username]
  ```

- **sudo**: Execute a command as another user (usually root)
  ```bash
  sudo command
  ```

- **useradd**: Add a new user
  ```bash
  sudo useradd username
  ```

- **passwd**: Change user password
  ```bash
  sudo passwd username
  ```

## Disk Usage and File Systems

- **df**: Display disk space usage
  ```bash
  df -h
  ```

- **du**: Estimate file space usage
  ```bash
  du [options] [directory]
  ```

## System Information

- **uname**: Display system information
  ```bash
  uname -a
  ```

- **uptime**: Show how long the system has been running
  ```bash
  uptime
  ```

- **hostname**: Display the system's hostname
  ```bash
  hostname
  ```

## Package Management (Debian/Ubuntu)

- **apt**: Manage packages
  ```bash
  sudo apt [options] package_name
  ```

- **apt-get**: Install packages
  ```bash
  sudo apt-get install package_name
  ```

## Miscellaneous Commands

- **history**: Display command history
  ```bash
  history
  ```

- **clear**: Clear the terminal screen
  ```bash
  clear
  ```

- **ln**: Create symbolic or hard links
  ```bash
  ln -s target link_name
  ```

- **man**: Display the manual page for a command
  ```bash
  man command_name
  ```


